Example Dataset

species <- tibble(id = c(1, 2, 3),
              name = c("Species1", "Species2", "Species3"))

abundance <- tibble(id = c(2, 3, 4),
              abundance = c(85, 90, 95))

Perform Joins

#left join
left_join(species, abundance, by = "id")
# A tibble: 3 Ã 3
     id name     abundance
  <dbl> <chr>        <dbl>
1     1 Species1        NA
2     2 Species2        85
3     3 Species3        90
#inner join
inner_join(species, abundance, by = "id")
# A tibble: 2 Ã 3
     id name     abundance
  <dbl> <chr>        <dbl>
1     2 Species2        85
2     3 Species3        90
#full join
full_join(species, abundance, by = "id")
# A tibble: 4 Ã 3
     id name     abundance
  <dbl> <chr>        <dbl>
1     1 Species1        NA
2     2 Species2        85
3     3 Species3        90
4     4 <NA>            95

cat("Without keep=TRUE, you get one key column (from x), already coalesced.

With keep=TRUE, you also get the original join keys from both tables, which may differ in type/format, revealing why they look different even though they matched. This is great for debugging joins and type issues (e.g., leading zeros).

")
Without keep=TRUE, you get one key column (from x), already coalesced.

With keep=TRUE, you also get the original join keys from both tables, which may differ in type/format, revealing why they look different even though they matched. This is great for debugging joins and type issues (e.g., leading zeros).

19.5.5.2 Exercises

#When finding if any party period overlapped with another party period we used q < q in the join_by()? Why? What happens if you remove this inequality?
cat("join_by(q < q) is a tie-breaker in a self non-equi join: it compares the right endpoint q of the left row to the q of the right row (i.e., x$q < y$q) to impose an ordering and keep only one orientation of each overlapping pair. Overlap conditions like start_x <= end_y & end_x >= start_y are symmetric, so without that extra inequality you get both (A,B) and (B,A) for every overlapping pair (and often self-matches if keys allow), doubling your counts and cluttering the result. The strict < removes duplicates (keeps the âupper triangleâ only) and prevents self-matches; if you drop it, youâll need a later distinct()/filter to de-duplicate.")
join_by(q < q) is a tie-breaker in a self non-equi join: it compares the right endpoint q of the left row to the q of the right row (i.e., x$q < y$q) to impose an ordering and keep only one orientation of each overlapping pair. Overlap conditions like start_x <= end_y & end_x >= start_y are symmetric, so without that extra inequality you get both (A,B) and (B,A) for every overlapping pair (and often self-matches if keys allow), doubling your counts and cluttering the result. The strict < removes duplicates (keeps the âupper triangleâ only) and prevents self-matches; if you drop it, youâll need a later distinct()/filter to de-duplicate.

19.6 Summary
